&ldquo;What was the biggest adjustment for you going from the military to the business world?&rdquo;
Several people have asked me that question, and my answer always surprises them.
&ldquo;In the military,&rdquo; I say, &ldquo;every individual has a lot more latitude and authority to act. In the business world, no one can do anything without explicit instructions.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Really? I thought it would be the other way around,&rdquo; they say.
&ldquo;That&rsquo;s the popular culture, but the truth is one-hundred eighty degrees the other way.

Paul Berry III made me laugh out loud. “Francis Slay hung out the vacancy sign but he’s running the Bates Motel.&quot;
We were talking about the Syrian refugees and Francis Slay’s insistence that hosting a lot of them is in the city’s vital interest.
Leaving aside the question of security and vetting for the refugees, why does Francis Slay want so desperately to host more people who have no jobs, no language, and little hope of flourishing in a city that, on most measures, is failing.

I hate to say &ldquo;I told you so.&rdquo;
But the St. Louis Post Dispatch has found that I may have been right on November 8. That&rsquo;s when I made the outlandish comment that the whole race issue at Mizzou is actually an abortion issue. I suspected that Planned Parenthood&rsquo;s vast lobbyist network is agitating leaders of left-leaning organizations trying to create general unrest.
**The manipulators would use campus racial unrest to demand restored privileges for Planned Parenthood.

Someone who met Bill Clinton told me, &ldquo;I rambled. He probably thought I was an idiot.&rdquo;
No. Bill Clinton wanted you to ramble. He wanted to make you the most important person in the room for two minutes. He listened for a nugget of information&ndash;a story&ndash;he could use in his next speech.
If you&rsquo;re running for office remember: the most important person in every room is the voter you&rsquo;re talking with.

&ldquo;What if everything goes wrong?&rdquo;
I remember asking myself that on the morning of Friday, February 27, 2009.
I was driving on I-44 headed to the Arch to host a Tea Party. My co-hosts were people I&rsquo;d never met: Dana Loesch, Gina Loudon, Ed Martin, Michelle Moore. Those were the three to offered to help. Others offered to speak: Jim Lembke, Shamed Dogan, and a few others. Others helped organize sign-making, food, sign-in sheets, and music.

&ldquo;What did you give up for Lent?&rdquo;
Ever get that one? Like it&rsquo;s something you&rsquo;re supposed to post on your Facebook page.
A very good priest I knew, Dom Oppenheimer, warned against revealing one&rsquo;s Lenten sacrifice.
&ldquo;When you tell others what you gave up for Lent, you&rsquo;re likely to feel some pride,&rdquo; he explained. &ldquo;But pride is the worst sin.&rdquo;
That actually makes a lot of sense when you think about.
